<span id="iii.ii-p11"></span> Noris, from this word, “villula,” a grange
or country house, concludes that Vincentius, at the time of writing,
though a monk, was not a monk of <span id="iii.ii-p11.1"></span>Lérins
for there could be no “villula” there then, Honoratus having found the
island desolate and without inhabitant, when he settled on it but a few
years previously, “vacantem insulam ob nimictatem squaloris, et
inaccessam venenatorum animalium metu.” *Histor. Pelag*. p. 251. Why,
however, may not the “villula” have been built subsequently to
Honoratus’s settlement and indeed, as a part of it? Whether Vincentius
was an inmate of the monastery of <span id="iii.ii-p11.2"></span>Lérins
at the time of writing the Commonitory or not, he was so eventually, and
died there.

